<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-846-093  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 846 093.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  Nov 28 1990 n1533 p15(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DTI ban plan under fire.(Britain's Department of Trade andIndustry seeks to ban reverse engineering)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schneider, Karl.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Reaction has been swift and strong to a proposed UK-backedamendment to a coming European Community directive.andP;  The amendmentwould ban reverse engineering, the process of analyzing hardwareor software to see how it works in order to produce a competingproduct.andP;  Under the terms of the amendment reverse engineeringwould still be allowed in order to produce 'connecting products'that complement and extend the function of existing equipment.andO;The amendment would not be enforced retroactively, so clone makerssuch as Amstrad and Apricot could continue to manufacture productsbased on previous reverse engineering efforts; should IBM modifyits design, however, they would be prevented from disassembling amicrocomputer in order to determine how to modify their units toremain competitive.andP;  Small and medium-sized computer makers warnthat this would prevent them from manufacturing compatibleproducts in Europe, effectively throwing control of the market toUS and Far Eastern competitors.andP;  Backing the amendment is theSoftware Action Group for Europe (SAGE), dominated by majorhardware vendors.andP;  It is expected that the representatives for the12 EC member states will back a compromise proposal that willeffectively kill the UK-backed amendment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     European Economic CommunityReverse EngineeringInternational TradeCompetitionUnited KingdomCompatible Hardware.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>